@startuml auth-flow
title Entra ID Managed Identity Auth Flow (Workload Identity → AuthXManager → AMR)

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam maxMessageSize 160

box "AKS platform (precondition, owned by platform team)" #F4F4F4
  participant "Workload Identity\nWebhook" as Webhook
end box

box "This app" #EAF2FF
  participant "AmrAuthConfig" as AuthConfig
  participant "DefaultAzureCredential" as Cred
  participant "AuthXManager\n(redis-authx-entraid)" as AuthX
  participant "JedisClientConfig\n(shared by all pools)" as ClientConfig
  participant "Jedis Connection\n(main pool / probe pools)" as Conn
  participant "EventRecorder\n(KPI 8: token lifecycle)" as EventRec
end box

participant "Entra ID (AAD)" as AAD
participant "AMR (Redis)" as AMR

== Pod scheduling (once, before this app runs) ==
Webhook -> Webhook : Pod carries label\nazure.workload.identity/use: "true"
note right of Webhook
  Injects AZURE_CLIENT_ID, AZURE_TENANT_ID,
  AZURE_FEDERATED_TOKEN_FILE, AZURE_AUTHORITY_HOST
  into the pod. This app never sets these itself.
end note

== App startup ==
AuthConfig -> Cred ** : new DefaultAzureCredentialBuilder().build()
note right of Cred
  Tries a chain: Environment, WorkloadIdentity,
  ManagedIdentity, AzureCli, ... first success wins.
  Locally: "az login" satisfies AzureCliCredential
  with **zero code changes**.
end note

AuthConfig -> AuthConfig : AzureTokenAuthConfigBuilder\n  .defaultAzureCredential(credential)\n  .scopes(amr.auth.token-scope)\n  .build()
AuthConfig -> AuthX ** : new AuthXManager(tokenAuthConfig)
AuthConfig -> AuthX : setListener(...)\naddPostAuthenticationHook(...)
AuthConfig -> AuthX : **start()**
note right of AuthConfig
  Must be called explicitly -- nothing in Jedis
  calls this automatically. Skipping it means
  every connection auth attempt fails with no
  token ever acquired (verified against source).
end note

activate AuthX
AuthX -> AAD : request token\n(scope: https://redis.azure.com/.default)
alt every credential in the chain fails
  AAD --> AuthX : no credential available
  AuthX --> AuthConfig : throws JedisAuthenticationException
  AuthConfig --> AuthConfig : Spring context refresh **aborts**\n(fail-fast -- see README)
else at least one credential succeeds
  AAD --> AuthX : access token (~1h lifetime)
  AuthX -> AuthX : store as currentToken
end
deactivate AuthX

AuthConfig -> ClientConfig ** : DefaultJedisClientConfig.builder()\n  .authXManager(authXManager)\n  .sslOptions(SslOptions.defaults())\n  .build()
note right of ClientConfig
  ONE AuthXManager instance is shared by every
  JedisClientConfig in the app: the main
  MultiDbClient pool AND both probe pools.
end note

== Connection open (any pool) ==
Conn -> ClientConfig : open connection using this config
ClientConfig -> AuthX : addConnection(connection)
note right of AuthX
  Connection registers a WEAK reference with the
  manager -- this is how renewal later finds it.
end note
Conn -> AMR : AUTH <token value> (TLS, port 10000)
AMR --> Conn : OK

== Background token renewal (recurs roughly hourly) ==
AuthX -> AAD : renew token before expiry
alt renewal succeeds
  AAD --> AuthX : new access token
  AuthX -> AuthX : authenticateConnections(token)
  loop every live registered connection
    AuthX -> Conn : connection.setCredentials(token)
    note right
      Re-authenticated IN PLACE --
      connection is never closed/recreated.
      This is the property KPI 8 / the
      "soak" preset exists to verify holds
      up under sustained load.
    end note
  end
  AuthX -> EventRec : postAuthenticationHook(token)
  EventRec -> EventRec : record TOKEN_RENEWAL / SUCCESS
else renewal fails
  AAD --> AuthX : error
  AuthX -> EventRec : onIdentityProviderError(reason)
  EventRec -> EventRec : record TOKEN_RENEWAL / FAILURE\n(ErrorCategory.AUTH_FAILURE)
end

@enduml
